Utterance: <synch>
Hi, welcome back! It’s nice to see you again. How have you been since our last session?
I’ve been pretty good, thanks! Just busy with work and planning the wedding.
That sounds exciting! How’s the wedding planning going?
It’s a bit overwhelming, honestly. There’s so much to think about, but we’re making progress.
I can imagine! Have you found any moments of joy in the planning process?
Yeah, definitely. Picking out the venue was really fun, and we’ve been able to taste some of the food options, which was nice.
That sounds wonderful! Food tasting must have been a highlight. How have you been feeling about the upcoming wedding overall?
I’m excited but also a little anxious. I want everything to go perfectly, but I know that’s unrealistic.
It’s completely normal to feel that way. What specifically are you anxious about?
I guess I worry about how everyone will get along and if there will be any drama. My family can be a bit… complicated.
That’s understandable. Family dynamics can add stress to any event. Have you thought about how you might manage those feelings on the day?
I’ve tried to remind myself that it’s about me and my partner, not everyone else. But I still can’t help but worry.
That’s a healthy perspective. Focusing on what matters most can help ground you. Would it be helpful to think about some coping strategies for that day?
Yeah, that might be good. I think I’ll need a plan to stay calm.
How about creating a small self-care routine for the day? Maybe a few moments of deep breathing or stepping away to gather your thoughts?
I like that idea. I could find a quiet spot to take a breather if I start feeling overwhelmed.
Exactly! You could even practice that technique here. Want to try a quick breathing exercise now?
Sure, that sounds good.
Great! Let’s take a deep breath in together… and out. In… and out. How does that feel?
It feels nice, actually. I can see how that would help.
Wonderful! You can use that technique anytime you feel anxious. It’s a great tool to have. Is there anything else you’d like to discuss today?
Well, I’ve been thinking more about my feelings of guilt regarding my potential. It’s been on my mind a lot.
That’s an important topic. What specifically about your potential is weighing on you?
I just feel like I could be doing more with my life, especially with starting a PhD program soon. I want to make sure I’m taking full advantage of the opportunity.

Utterance: It’s commendable that you want to make the most of it. What does “doing more” look like for you?
I guess I want to be productive and also find a way to contribute meaningfully to my field.
How might you measure that productivity? What steps could you take to feel fulfilled in this new journey?
I think setting small, achievable goals would help. Like focusing on my coursework and networking with others in the program.
Those sound like excellent steps. Would you like to outline some specific goals for the next few weeks?
Sure! I want to read a couple of articles each week, reach out to a few professors, and maybe even attend some seminars.
Those are fantastic goals! Setting a timeline for each could keep you accountable. How does that sound?
That sounds great! I feel more motivated just thinking about it.
I’m glad to hear that! Remember, it’s about progress, not perfection. How do you feel now about your upcoming PhD program?
I feel a bit more excited and less anxious. I think having a plan helps.
That’s great to hear! I’m proud of you for taking these steps. Is there anything else you’d like to cover today?
I think that’s about it for now. I’m feeling good about our conversation.
I am too! Let’s keep working on those goals, and I look forward to hearing about your progress next time. Have a great week!
Thanks, Ellie! You too.
Goodbye!
Goodbye!
